Inflation, in Europe, has come up with food
The accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was higher than in the forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, indicating the Office for Statistics of the European Community located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the United States, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not decrease the direct interest rate by saying that lower interest rates, with higher commodity prices and lower unemployment rates, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: "It is necessary to deter" inflation so as not to have any further action on this issue.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record over the past 12 years and in Spain, it is raised from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has declined due to the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
The market price for cereals increased by 88 per cent and the soybean price also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, the world oil price increased by 52 percent, and last month, a silver barrel cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 in 2008 to 2.5 per cent this year, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to the analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3%, but the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce its management rate twice in 2008.
