Many hospitals make the economy of disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the misuse of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
Hospitals' hygiene conditions, insufficient number of beds, overload of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the doctor in charge of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also make the economy of disinfectants
A MRSA infection has not long been diagnosed in the János hospital trauma service.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The disease has been isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injury from a serious car accident came out of the hospital but shortly after it had to return because of a MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to perform an important operation because of the bacteria in their body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, a doctor at the National Epidemiology Centre.
It is known that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen who has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSAs, in other words by staphylococcus aureus resistant to methylylline oxacilline.
A third of the people are carriers of the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, amygdalitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well resistant bacteria that will spread rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In the case of temporary or prolonged immunosuppression of the immune system, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as trauma or septic infection, on the elderly, small weights or with a weakened body.
According to hospital manager János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily hospital routine.
In particular, the infection must not be confused with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only or we do not search for it, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the caring staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks, and we have appropriate antibiotics to care for them," Tibor Nyulasi said.
In priority, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not in mode
The large majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and residences for elderly people, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA.
However, microbiological collection is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these reviews.
Most cases see only the day if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, the doctor in charge of the epidemiological center said.
The European Union has strict recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian directives for the management of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to target antibiotic therapy, in other words microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals make the economy of disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA produces one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, to wear gloves and protective masks. However, important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of gouttelettes and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the contaminated disease cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, beds are often too close to each other while in the end of the epidemic, the patients should be separated from each other by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are many, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is less demonstrable or the proliferation of pathogen agent may be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant costs for social security funds, which is why we are fighting this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a programme to prevent or reduce the impact of MRSAs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) shows among its priorities the prevention of the impact of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
