British Army units report on the video-sharing site of their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with a view to becoming popular.
First of all, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has been passionate about YouTube: the special units involved in Afghanistan are charging video sequences on Taliban operations since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken with the help of miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are controlled in the general area of air force operations in Kandahar and are then transferred to London or compatriots to charge them on the Internet.
The political message is irreversible
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been seen by more than 75 thousand people.
The British Defence Department registered as "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 and provides videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Commonwealth Office and the international peacekeeping forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed online to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to publicize the real goals of the presence of the army abroad.
The propaganda published by this route costs virtually nothing in relation to the usual television recruitment ads, as reported to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a consultant in defence, and, on the other hand, it also inevitably brings a political message because it is in a special form justifying the well-founded military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have made a game
