They recall that, following a greater publicity given to the reorganisation of the Hungarian radical and extreme right groups since fall 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since summer 2007 and have been known as the "national self-defence association".
"The common treaty of these meetings is that they are defined as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their adherents to defence missions (disasters, national defence, defence of the order), armed if necessary, to exceed, by mentioning the incapacity of the police, the army, otherwise said of the state," they added.
