The old history is covered, a decoupling of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, a wooden box based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museum was presented in 1968 - with the Warhol agreement - of hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: they did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
This was not about works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wood boxes in Sweden, which were not also exposed to Moderna Museet.
Today, witnesses of the time speak of about fifteen wooden cassettes that would then enter the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the title "Type Stockholm".
Some of them achieved more than $100,000 in sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum claimed, on the contrary, later that about one hundred wooden cassettes had been produced and exposed in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have given it to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén caisses were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, head of the Modern Museum, examined, next to the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their stratified panels were first printed and punched, then applied with a paint brush to white oil.
